      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A very preterm infant, 6 days old and on enteral feeding, presents with acute symptoms including crying with leg flexion, severe abdominal distension with visible bowel loops, temperature instability, and lethargy. An abdominal X-ray reveals the presence of portal venous gas, a critical finding in this clinical context. Based on the clinical presentation and radiographic findings, which stage of necrotizing enterocolitis (NEC) is this very preterm infant most likely experiencing?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3047800",
